**Cluster headache** is a [neurological
disorder](neurological_disorder "wikilink") characterized by recurrent
severe [headaches](headache "wikilink") on one side of the head,
typically around the [eye(s)](eye "wikilink").[1] There is often
accompanying eye watering, [nasal
congestion](nasal_congestion "wikilink"), or swelling around the
[eye](eye "wikilink") on the affected side.[2] These symptoms typically
last 15 minutes to 3 hours.[3] Attacks often occur in clusters which
typically last for weeks or months and occasionally more than a year.[4]

The cause is unknown,[5] but is most likely related to dysfunction of
the posterior [hypothalamus](hypothalamus "wikilink").[6] Risk factors
include a history of exposure to [tobacco
smoke](tobacco_smoke "wikilink") and a [family
history](Family_history_(medicine) "wikilink") of the condition.[7]
Exposures which may trigger attacks include
[alcohol](ethanol "wikilink"),
[nitroglycerin](nitroglycerin_(medication) "wikilink"), and
[histamine](histamine "wikilink").[8] They are a [primary headache
disorder](primary_headache_disorder "wikilink") of the [trigeminal
autonomic cephalalgias](trigeminal_autonomic_cephalalgia "wikilink")
type.[9] Diagnosis is based on symptoms.[10]

Recommended management includes
[lifestyle](Lifestyle_(sociology) "wikilink") adaptations such as
avoiding potential triggers.[11] Treatments for acute attacks include
[oxygen](Oxygen_therapy "wikilink") or a fast-acting
[triptan](triptan "wikilink").[12][13] Measures recommended to decrease
the frequency of attacks include [steroid
injections](steroid_injections "wikilink"),
[galcanezumab](galcanezumab "wikilink"),
[civamide](Zucapsaicin "wikilink"), [verapamil](verapamil "wikilink"),
or oral [glucocorticoids](Glucocorticoid "wikilink") such as
[prednisone](prednisone "wikilink").[14][15][16] [Nerve
stimulation](Nerve_stimulation "wikilink") or surgery may occasionally
be used if other measures are not effective.[17][18]

The condition affects about 0.1% of the general population at some point
in their life and 0.05% in any given year.[19] The condition usually
first occurs between 20 and 40 years of age.[20] Men are affected about
four times more often than women.[21] Cluster headaches are named for
the occurrence of groups of headache attacks (clusters).[22] They have
also been referred to as "suicide headaches".[23]

## Signs and symptoms

Cluster headaches are recurring bouts of severe unilateral headache
attacks.[24][25] The duration of a typical cluster headache ranges from
about 15 to 180 minutes.[26] About 75% of untreated attacks last less
than 60 minutes.[27] However, women may have longer and more severe
cluster headaches.[28]

The onset of an attack is rapid and typically without an
[aura](Aura_(symptom) "wikilink"). Preliminary sensations of pain in the
general area of attack, referred to as "shadows", may signal an imminent
cluster headache, or these symptoms may linger after an attack has
passed, or between attacks.[29] Though cluster headaches are strictly
unilateral, there are some documented cases of "side-shift" between
cluster periods,[30] or, rarely, simultaneous (within the same cluster
period) bilateral cluster headaches.[31]

### Pain

The pain occurs only on one side of the head, around the eye,
particularly behind or above the eye, in the temple. The pain is
typically greater than in other headache conditions, including
[migraines](migraine "wikilink"), and is usually described as burning,
stabbing, drilling or squeezing.[32] While suicide is rare, those with
cluster headaches may experience suicidal thoughts (giving the
alternative name "suicide headache" or "suicidal headache").[33][34] The
term "headache" does not adequately convey the severity of the
condition; the disease may be the most painful condition known to
medical science.[35][36] [Dr. Peter Goadsby](Peter_Goadsby "wikilink"),
Professor of Clinical Neurology at University College London, a leading
researcher on the condition has commented:

### Other symptoms

The typical symptoms of cluster headache include grouped occurrence and
recurrence (cluster) of headache attack, severe unilateral orbital,
supraorbital and/or temporal pain. If left untreated, attack frequency
may range from one attack every two days to eight attacks per
day.[37][38] Cluster headache attack is accompanied by at least one of
the following autonomic symptoms: [drooping
eyelid](Ptosis_(eyelid) "wikilink"), [pupil
constriction](miosis "wikilink"), redness of the
[conjunctiva](conjunctiva "wikilink"),
[tearing](lacrimation "wikilink"), [runny nose](rhinorrhea "wikilink")
and less commonly, [facial blushing](facial_blushing "wikilink"),
swelling, or sweating, typically appearing on the same side of the head
as the pain.[39] Similar to a migraine, sensitivity to light
([photophobia](photophobia "wikilink")) or noise
([phonophobia](phonophobia "wikilink")) may occur during a cluster
headache. Nausea is a rare symptom although it has been reported.[40]

Restlessness (for example, pacing or rocking back and forth) may occur.
Secondary effects may include the inability to organize thoughts and
plans, physical exhaustion, confusion, agitation, aggressiveness,
depression, and anxiety.[41]

People with cluster headaches may dread facing another headache and
adjust their physical or social activities around a possible future
occurrence. Likewise they may seek assistance to accomplish what would
otherwise be normal tasks. They may hesitate to make plans because of
the regularity, or conversely, the
[unpredictability](unpredictability "wikilink") of the pain schedule.
These factors can lead to generalized [anxiety
disorders](anxiety_disorder "wikilink"), [panic
disorder](panic_disorder "wikilink"),[42] serious [depressive
disorders](depressive_disorder "wikilink"),[43] social withdrawal and
isolation.[44]

Cluster headaches have been recently associated with obstructive [sleep
apnea](sleep_apnea "wikilink") comorbidity.[45]

### Recurrence

Cluster headaches may occasionally be referred to as "alarm clock
headache" because of the regularity of their recurrence. Cluster
headaches often awaken individuals from sleep. Both individual attacks
and the cluster grouping can have a metronomic regularity; attacks
typically striking at a precise time of day each morning or night. The
recurrence of headache cluster grouping may occur more often around
[solstices](solstice "wikilink"), or seasonal changes, sometimes showing
circannual periodicity. Conversely, attack frequency may be highly
unpredictable, showing no periodicity at all. These observations have
prompted researchers to speculate an involvement or dysfunction of the
hypothalamus. The hypothalamus controls the body's "biological clock"
and [circadian rhythm](circadian_rhythm "wikilink").[46][47] In episodic
cluster headache, attacks occur once or more daily, often at the same
time each day for a period of several weeks, followed by a headache-free
period lasting weeks, months, or years. Approximately 10â€“15% of cluster
headaches are [chronic](Chronic_(medicine) "wikilink"), with multiple
headaches occurring every day for years, sometimes without any
remission.[48]

In accordance with the International Headache Society (IHS) diagnostic
criteria, cluster headaches occurring in two or more cluster periods,
lasting from 7 to 365 days with a pain-free
[remission](Remission_(medicine) "wikilink") of one month or longer
between the headache attacks may be classified as episodic. If headache
attacks occur for more than a year without pain-free remission of at
least three months, the condition is classified as chronic.[49] Chronic
cluster headaches both occur and recur without any remission periods
between cycles; there may be variation in cycles, meaning the frequency
and severity of attacks may change without predictability for a period
of time. The frequency, severity, and duration of headache attacks
experienced by people during these cycles varies between individuals and
does not demonstrate complete remission of the episodic form. The
condition may change unpredictably from chronic to episodic and from
episodic to chronic.[50]

